```
class C1
{
    public virtual void M1(int[] p)
    {
    }
    public virtual void M2(int p)
    {
    }
}

class C2 : C1
{
    public override void M1(params int[] p)
    {
    }

    public override void M2(int p = 1)
    {
    }

    void Test()
    {
        M1(1, 2, 3); //  error CS1501: No overload for method 'M1' takes 3 arguments
        M2();
    }
}
```

Observed:
```
 error CS1501: No overload for method 'M1' takes 3 arguments
```

Note that the fact whether a parameter is optional is derived from the most overridden form of the target method,
but the fact whether a parameter is `params` is derived from the least overridden form of the method.

It also looks like, at least in some basic declaration scenarios, C# silently transfers `params' modifier
from an overridden method to the overriding method. Like in this scenario:
```
class C1
{
    public virtual void M1(params int[] p)
    {
    }
}

class C2 : C1
{
    public override void M1(int[] p)
    {
    }
}
```

However, the overridden method and the overriding method do not have to be defined in the same assembly, and, therefore, can be versioned separately. `params` modifier can be added to (or removed from) the overridden method after the overriding method is compiled. 
Therefore, we can run into a case when an overridden method has `params` modifier, but the overriding doesn't have it.

It would be good to review references to `ParameterSymbol.IsParams` with all that in mind. For example, the following helper in
the ```Binder```:
```
        private static readonly Func<PropertySymbol, bool> s_isIndexedPropertyWithNonOptionalArguments = property =>
            {
                if (property.IsIndexer || !property.IsIndexedProperty)
                {
                    return false;
                }

                Debug.Assert(property.ParameterCount > 0);
                var parameter = property.Parameters[0];
                return !parameter.IsOptional && !parameter.IsParams;
            };
```
might produce result inconsistent with what overload resolution would "think" about the property in relation to `params` modifier
on overriding property. That is not to mention the fact, that `params` isn't necessarily checked on the last parameter here.

